### PHP OOP - Inheritance

Inheritance allows a class to inherit properties and methods from another class.

### extends Keyword

```php
<?php
class Animal {
    public $name;

    public function __construct($name) {
        $this->name = $name;
    }

    public function makeSound() {
        return "Some sound";
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    public function makeSound() {
        return "Woof!";
    }

    public function fetch() {
        return "$this->name is fetching";
    }
}

$dog = new Dog("Buddy");
echo $dog->makeSound(); // Woof!
echo $dog->fetch();     // Buddy is fetching
?>
```

### Overriding

Child classes can override methods by redefining them.

```php
<?php
class ParentClass {
    protected function greet() {
        return "Hello from parent";
    }
}

class ChildClass extends ParentClass {
    public function greet() {
        return "Hello from child";
    }
}
?>
```

### parent Keyword

```php
<?php
class Child extends Parent {
    public function greet() {
        return parent::greet() . " and child";
    }
}
?>
```

### final Keyword

Prevents a method from being overridden or a class from being extended.

```php
<?php
final class MathUtils {
    public static function add($a, $b) {
        return $a + $b;
    }
}

// This would cause an error:
// class BetterMath extends MathUtils { }
?>
```

> **Key Point:** PHP supports single inheritance (a class can only extend one parent). Use `parent::` to call the parent class's methods.
